.TH hashline-read 1  "read " 
.SH NAME
read \- Read a file and output hashline\-formatted content
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBread\fR [\fB\-\-start\-line\fR] [\fB\-\-lines\fR] [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] <\fIFILE\fR> 
.SH DESCRIPTION
Read a file and output each line prefixed with its LINE:HASH anchor.
.PP
Each line of output has the form:
.PP
LINENUM:HASH|CONTENT
.PP
where HASH is a 2\-char hex string derived from xxHash32 of the whitespace\-stripped line content. Use \-\-start\-line and \-\-lines to read a specific range â€” useful for verifying edits without re\-reading an entire large file.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-start\-line\fR \fI<START_LINE>\fR [default: 1]
Starting line number (1\-indexed, default 1)
.TP
\fB\-\-lines\fR \fI<LINES>\fR
Maximum number of lines to output
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help (see a summary with \*(Aq\-h\*(Aq)
.TP
<\fIFILE\fR>
File path to read
.SH EXTRA
EXAMPLES
Read the whole file:
hashline read src/main.rs

Read lines 50\-74:
hashline read \-\-start\-line 50 \-\-lines 25 src/main.rs

Read from line 100 to end of file:
hashline read \-\-start\-line 100 src/main.rs
